text: I always find it fascinating when cards I know are really great wind up not being good in a particular deck I have. I've ran into it with Faithless Looting and Search for Azcanta recently. It's not that they're not good in EDH or anything; both are excellent cards. They're just not what I want in my deck.
Which deck(s)?
I always find that slightly depressing, especially when I'm excited about a card
Your first mistake was liking a blue card...

text: Both are ones with no graveyard recursion, and without a lot of fat. In the formats and decks where both get played you're either getting gas putting stuff in the yard, or trying to get to that card that wins the game, of which there are multiples in the deck. In my case neither of those applied, so most of the time I found myself just wanting bulk draw in those slots.
I wanted to be casting [[light up the stage]] way more than Faithless Looting for example

Looting also has the problem of seeing it in 60 card formats and being so good that they assume it’s the same thing in commander which it definitely isn’t. It’s the red brainstorm when it comes to getting played purely off reputation alone, never mind that looting is actively card disadvantage in a vacuum
I still slot it into most red decks at first. It always has a better return than Brainstorm, so I’m not sure if that comparison is entirely accurate.
Spend a mana, go down a card and loot twice. At least brainstorm leaves you at parity when it comes to card quantity.

If you’re looking for card advantage this is scientifically not it. Card filtering and velocity, sure. But it’s not leaving you even at parity. You have to hope the cards that you drew into were better than the 2 you discarded and that you lost a card from hand for it to leave your hand “better”

I’m not going to speak for other formats, but at least in EDH, I’d rather *see* more cards than have more cards in my hand. It’s digging me down one more and giving me the option to play it again later when I need it.
I understand what you’re saying, and to a degree I don’t disagree, but perhaps I dislike Brainstorm too much :rolling_on_the_floor_laughing:

Filtering and velocity is also a whole different thing when you need to hit that one of three remaining Bolts or 2 remaning Lava Spikes in your last 29 cards vs trying to hit 1 thing in your remaing 78
Same is true of Azcanta, really. Seeing 2 of your last 30 cards when you have 7-8 ones in the deck that may win a game is different than seeing 2 of 75, none of which may be game winners

I cut Looting from my decks a bunch, I just always start with it, and I also think that more times than not will make the cut over Brainstorm. That being said, this conversation is reminding me that I need to pick up a couple of Azcantas for Scarab God and Inalla :eyes:
